'''Lee–Jackson Day''' is a [[legal holiday]] celebrated in the [[Virginia|Commonwealth of Virginia]] in the [[United States|U.S.]], for the birthdays of [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] generals [[Robert E. Lee]] and [[Stonewall Jackson|Thomas J. "Stonewall" Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lee Jackson Day, Lexington VA|url=http://www.leejacksonday.webs.com/}}</ref> The original holiday, created in 1889, celebrated Lee's birthday on January 19th. Jackson's name was added to the holiday in 1904; his birthday was January 21st.
In 1983, the holiday was merged with the new Federal holiday, [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day]], as [[Lee–Jackson–King Day]] in Virginia. This merger was reversed in 2000.
Lee–Jackson Day is currently observed on the second Friday in January, which precedes [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day]] (the third Monday in January). Typical events include a wreath-laying ceremony with military honors, a Civil War themed parade, symposia, and a gala ball.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lee–Jackson Day|url=http://www.virginia.org/Listings/EventsAndExhibits/LeeJacksonDay/|publisher=Virginia.org}}</ref> State offices are closed for both holidays.<ref name="stateholiday1">{{cite web | url =http://www.dhrm.virginia.gov/payandholidaycalendar.html |title=Pay and Holiday Calendar |publisher=Virginia DHRM |accessdate=January 10, 2011}}</ref>
Many Virginia cities, such as [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]], [[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]], [[Hampton, Virginia|Hampton]], [[Newport News, Virginia|Newport News]], [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]], [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], and [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]], choose not to observe Lee–Jackson Day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlottesville stops observance of Lee–Jackson Day|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/charlottesville-stops-observance-of-leejackson-day/31580906|website=www.wdbj7.com|accessdate=March 3, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150305161909/http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/charlottesville-stops-observance-of-leejackson-day/31580906|archivedate=March 5, 2015|df=}}</ref> In 2017, the [[Blacksburg, Virginia|Town of Blacksburg]] decided to stop observing the day as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Town of Blacksburg Rules & Regulations Revisions July 11, 2017|url=http://blacksburg.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=20&clip_id=2042&meta_id=77323|website=Town of Blacksburg|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>
